@Mr Brightside No, airflow definitely helps in making it more efficient if air cooled, but is not needed.  You are making assumptions based on the conclusion you want to reach, not on facts or logic reasoning.  

There are way better systems for regenerative breaking than compressed air ever can become. What you think when you obviously lack basic understanding of the problems, is completely irrelevant. 

How do you think you have realized significant value in the technique that is older than cars, that apparently no manufacturer realized since the invention of the car? Do you think you are god? Elon Musk? Leonardo da Vinci? Or even smarter than them?

@aomanchutube

 I was testing an electrolyser that I made from canning jars. It had a small torch at the end. I was testing it for the fist time and had two levels of what I thought were effective flame traps. Luckily, I put a steel 5 gal paint can over it , lit the torch and watched the flame travel up the hose. All the while, I thought the flame would be trapped. 15 seconds from the time I lit the torch, it exploded under the can that was still loud enough to make my ears ring. When I finally took the can off the apparatus I made, there was no piece of glass larger than 1/4 inch and the top of the can was dented.
I still wonder how things would have been if I had not put the can on top, probably like a glass grenade going off in my workshop.
